2026-07-05T16:40:14 | DS on-stuck escalation ladder = builder-side ground-truth instrument + discovery channel for unsorted coding questions. A builder (DS) that hits an under-designed ticket CANNOT absorb the design gap the way CC can — it flails or burns its whole budget (real instance: this weekend's architect paged files to budget-exhaustion with no 'I'm stuck' exit). On-stuck escalation is CP1-with-a-body for the builder. Cost-ordered ladder (not alternatives): (1) tree/build-packet answer [free — the win]; (2) drop-a-ticket-on-stuck [cheap, async — DS files the question it couldn't answer, sets its ticket needs-design, moves to next work; dropped ticket is a durable labeled artifact]; (3) stop/HALT [blocks; HALT primitive built-but-unused]; (4) call-CC [expensive, sync — spends the resource we starve; its FREQUENCY is the metric]. Distribution over rungs IS the starve-curve for the builder ('get inside the process'). DS getting genuinely stuck is reality resisting — unfakeable, uncoupled from DS's self-model — so the stuck-stream is the builder-side of the same temporal firewall as the grounding-spine work; pre-registration and stuck-on-execution are two faces of one instrument. Closes to the question-sorting theory: a well-labeled stuck = one unsorted question in the coding domain surfacing; the drop-ticket stream is the worklist to sort into the tree next (stronger DS without a smarter model). Caveat (same as verdict_strength): raw 'stuck' is low-info; value is naming WHICH question defeated it — the hard design problem hiding here. Not building today; to be /sorted into coding-loop design | D-ds-builder-leveling D-coding-loop-redesign-aider-survey-2026-07-04 D-proof-program-grounding-spine-2026-07-05
